&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Antivirus&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span align-items:=&quot;&quot; display:=&quot;&quot; gap:=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;img cdn.testbook.com=&quot;&quot; height=&quot;&quot; lms_creative_elements=&quot;&quot; resources=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span font-size:=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;&quot; vertical-align:=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Antivirus&lt;/strong&gt; is a software program designed to detect, prevent, and remove malicious programs, such as viruses, worms, and Trojans, from your system.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It works by scanning files and programs to identify and eliminate malware threats before they can cause damage.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Antivirus software typically includes features such as real-time protection, scheduled scans, and quarantine for suspicious files.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Modern antivirus solutions also protect against phishing, ransomware, and other advanced cyber threats.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Using an antivirus is essential for maintaining the security and integrity of your devices and data.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span align-items:=&quot;&quot; display:=&quot;&quot; gap:=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;img cdn.testbook.com=&quot;&quot; height=&quot;&quot; lms_creative_elements=&quot;&quot; resources=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span font-size:=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;&quot; vertical-align:=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Features of Antivirus:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Real-Time Protection:&lt;/strong&gt; Continuously monitors the system for threats and blocks them as they arise.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Automatic Updates:&lt;/strong&gt; Regularly updates the virus definitions to stay protected from the latest threats.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;System Scans:&lt;/strong&gt; Provides options for quick scans, full scans, or custom scans to target specific areas of the device.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Types of Malware Detected by Antivirus:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Viruses:&lt;/strong&gt; Malicious software that spreads by infecting other files or programs.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ransomware:&lt;/strong&gt; Encrypts files and demands payment to restore access.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Spyware:&lt;/strong&gt; Secretly collects information about the user without their consent.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Trojans:&lt;/strong&gt; Disguises itself as legitimate software to gain access to systems.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Advantages of Using Antivirus:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Protects against malware attacks that could compromise sensitive data.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Ensures safe browsing by blocking harmful websites and phishing attempts.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Improves system performance by removing malicious files and programs.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Important Points:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Antivirus software should be regularly updated to remain effective against new threats.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Some antivirus solutions offer additional features such as parental controls and VPN services.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Using a trusted and reputed antivirus provider is crucial for optimal protection.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;TCP/IP&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;TCP/IP&lt;/strong&gt; is the fundamental protocol suite for communication over the internet and other networks.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It consists of two main protocols: &lt;strong&gt;Transmission Control Protocol (TCP)&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;Internet Protocol (IP)&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;TCP ensures reliable data transmission by establishing connections, managing data flow, and checking for errors.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;IP is responsible for addressing and routing packets of data so they reach the correct destination.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;TCP/IP&lt;/strong&gt; is widely used in various applications, including web browsing, email, and file transfer, due to its robustness and reliability.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Uses of TCP/IP:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Web Browsing:&lt;/strong&gt; TCP/IP is the backbone for HTTP/HTTPS protocols used for accessing websites.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Email Communication:&lt;/strong&gt; Protocols like SMTP, IMAP, and POP3 operate over TCP/IP for sending and receiving emails.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;File Transfers:&lt;/strong&gt; Protocols such as FTP and SFTP use TCP/IP for transferring files between systems.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Streaming:&lt;/strong&gt; TCP/IP supports multimedia streaming services, including video and audio content delivery.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Key Features of TCP/IP:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Scalability:&lt;/strong&gt; TCP/IP can support networks of various sizes, from small local networks to the global internet.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Interoperability:&lt;/strong&gt; It enables communication between devices running different operating systems and hardware platforms.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Layered Architecture:&lt;/strong&gt; The protocol is divided into layers, making it modular and easier to troubleshoot and develop.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Advantages of Using TCP/IP:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Widely accepted and used across various platforms and devices.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Ensures reliable communication through error detection and correction mechanisms.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Supports a wide range of applications, including web services, email, and streaming.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Important Points:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;TCP/IP is a connection-oriented protocol, which ensures data integrity and reliability.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It uses logical IP addresses for identification and routing, ensuring seamless communication between devices.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It supports both IPv4 and IPv6 versions, ensuring compatibility with modern networking requirements.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;7&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;OSI (Open Systems Interconnection)&lt;/strong&gt; model is a conceptual framework used to understand and implement network communication protocols in seven distinct layers.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These seven layers are &lt;strong&gt;Physical, Data Link, Network, Transport, Session, Presentation, and Application&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The model helps standardize network communication and ensures interoperability between different systems and technologies.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Each layer has specific functions and responsibilities, ensuring effective data transfer between devices on a network.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Understanding the OSI model is essential for network professionals and students in the field of computer networking.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Functions of OSI Layers:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Physical Layer:&lt;/strong&gt; Deals with the physical connection between devices, including cables, switches, and signals.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Data Link Layer:&lt;/strong&gt; Ensures error-free data transfer between adjacent network nodes.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Network Layer:&lt;/strong&gt; Manages routing and forwarding of data packets across networks.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Transport Layer:&lt;/strong&gt; Provides reliable data transfer and error detection between host systems.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Session Layer:&lt;/strong&gt; Manages sessions and controls dialogues between applications.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Presentation Layer:&lt;/strong&gt; Ensures data is in a readable format for the application layer, handling encryption and compression.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Application Layer:&lt;/strong&gt; Provides network services directly to the end-users, such as email and file transfer.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Advantages of the OSI Model:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Promotes modular engineering and simplifies troubleshooting in network communication.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Enables interoperability between hardware and software from different vendors.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Facilitates the development of new networking technologies and protocols.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Important Points:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The OSI model is a reference model and does not perform actual functions in networking.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Real-world networking protocols like TCP/IP map to the OSI model for better understanding.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;While the OSI model has seven layers, the TCP/IP model has four layers, combining some OSI layers.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The Correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Transistors&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;color: (33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The second generation of computers (1956-1963) witnessed the replacement of &lt;strong&gt;vacuum tubes&lt;/strong&gt; with &lt;strong&gt;transistors&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Transistors&lt;/strong&gt; were smaller in size, consumed less power, and were more reliable compared to vacuum tubes.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This transition significantly reduced the &lt;strong&gt;size&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;heat generation&lt;/strong&gt;, and &lt;strong&gt;power consumption&lt;/strong&gt; of computers, making them more efficient.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The invention of the &lt;strong&gt;transistor&lt;/strong&gt; in 1947 by John Bardeen, William Shockley, and Walter Brattain at Bell Labs revolutionized the electronics industry.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Transistors allowed computers to operate much faster due to their ability to switch &lt;strong&gt;on and off states&lt;/strong&gt; rapidly.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Second-generation computers used transistors for applications such as &lt;strong&gt;business data processing&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;scientific research&lt;/strong&gt;, and &lt;strong&gt;engineering&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Examples of second-generation computers include &lt;strong&gt;IBM 1401&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;UNIVAC III&lt;/strong&gt;, and &lt;strong&gt;CDC 1604&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The development of transistors laid the foundation for modern electronics and paved the way for further miniaturization in subsequent computer generations.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Integrated Circuits (ICs)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;ICs&lt;/strong&gt; were introduced during the &lt;strong&gt;third generation of computers&lt;/strong&gt; (1964-1971).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;They consist of multiple transistors, resistors, and capacitors integrated onto a single silicon chip.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;ICs further reduced the size and increased the speed of computers compared to transistor-based systems.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Examples of third-generation computers include the &lt;strong&gt;IBM System/360&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;PDP-8&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Semiconductors&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Semiconductors&lt;/strong&gt; are materials with electrical conductivity between that of conductors and insulators.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Transistors are made from semiconductor materials like &lt;strong&gt;silicon&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;germanium&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Semiconductors are the fundamental building blocks for modern electronic components, including &lt;strong&gt;transistors&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;diodes&lt;/strong&gt;, and &lt;strong&gt;ICs&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Microprocessors&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Microprocessors&lt;/strong&gt; were introduced during the &lt;strong&gt;fourth generation of computers&lt;/strong&gt; (1971-present).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A microprocessor integrates the &lt;strong&gt;CPU functions&lt;/strong&gt; onto a single chip, further reducing size and increasing efficiency.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Examples of early microprocessors include the &lt;strong&gt;Intel 4004&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;Intel 8080&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Bar&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span align-items:=&quot;&quot; display:=&quot;&quot; gap:=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;img cdn.testbook.com=&quot;&quot; height=&quot;&quot; lms_creative_elements=&quot;&quot; resources=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span font-size:=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;&quot; vertical-align:=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A &lt;strong&gt;Bar chart&lt;/strong&gt; is used in MS Excel to illustrate the comparison among individual items.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It represents data with rectangular bars, where the length of the bar is proportional to the value it represents.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Bar charts are particularly useful for visualizing categorical data or comparing different groups.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They can be displayed horizontally or vertically based on the requirement.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The bars in a bar chart are separated by spaces to clearly distinguish each category or data point.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span align-items:=&quot;&quot; display:=&quot;&quot; gap:=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;img cdn.testbook.com=&quot;&quot; height=&quot;&quot; lms_creative_elements=&quot;&quot; resources=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span font-size:=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;&quot; vertical-align:=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Comparison with Other Chart Types:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Column Chart:&lt;/strong&gt; Similar to bar charts but used for vertical representation of data comparisons.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Line Chart:&lt;/strong&gt; Used for showing trends or changes over time, represented by a continuous line.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Area Chart:&lt;/strong&gt; Similar to line charts but filled with color below the line to emphasize magnitude.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Advantages of Using Bar Charts:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Simple and easy to understand for comparing data across different categories.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Effective in presenting large datasets with clear distinctions.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Provides visual emphasis on the differences between categories.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Important Points:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Bar charts are best suited for categorical data rather than continuous data.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Ensure proper labeling of axes and bars for better clarity and understanding.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Use consistent colors and spacing to avoid visual clutter in the chart.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Returns the cosine of x&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span align-items:=&quot;&quot; display:=&quot;&quot; gap:=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;img cdn.testbook.com=&quot;&quot; height=&quot;&quot; lms_creative_elements=&quot;&quot; resources=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span font-size:=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;&quot; vertical-align:=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;cos(x)&lt;/strong&gt; is a method in the Math object of programming languages like JavaScript. It calculates the cosine of a number, where the number is expressed in radians.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The cosine function is a trigonometric function that relates the ratio of the adjacent side to the hypotenuse of a right triangle.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This method is used in various mathematical and engineering calculations where trigonometric functions play a role.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;To convert degrees to radians, multiply the degree value by &lt;strong&gt;&amp;pi;/180&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The output of &lt;strong&gt;Math.cos(x)&lt;/strong&gt; is always a value between -1 and 1.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span align-items:=&quot;&quot; display:=&quot;&quot; gap:=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;img cdn.testbook.com=&quot;&quot; height=&quot;&quot; lms_creative_elements=&quot;&quot; resources=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span font-size:=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;&quot; vertical-align:=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Examples of Math.cos(x):&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Math.cos(0):&lt;/strong&gt; Returns 1 because the cosine of 0 radians is 1.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Math.cos(Math.PI/2):&lt;/strong&gt; Returns 0 because the cosine of &amp;pi;/2 radians is 0.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Math.cos(Math.PI):&lt;/strong&gt; Returns -1 because the cosine of &amp;pi; radians is -1.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Applications of the cosine function:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Used in physics and engineering to model waveforms, such as sound and light waves.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Helps calculate angles and distances in navigation and GPS systems.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Widely applied in computer graphics for rendering and animation purposes.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Important Points:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The argument of the &lt;strong&gt;cos(x)&lt;/strong&gt; method must be in radians. To convert degrees to radians, use the formula: radians = degrees &amp;times; (&amp;pi;/180).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The cosine function is periodic with a period of 2&amp;pi;, meaning &lt;strong&gt;cos(x) = cos(x + 2&amp;pi;k)&lt;/strong&gt; for any integer k.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is essential to ensure the input values are within the expected range to avoid calculation errors.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
